```java
private void replaceReferencesToThis(Node node, String name) {
    if (NodeUtil.isFunction(node)) {
      return;
    }

    // Copy children to avoid ConcurrentModificationException
    Node[] children = node.children().toArray(new Node[0]);
    for (Node child : children) {
      if (NodeUtil.isThis(child)) {
        Node newName = Node.newString(Token.NAME, name);
        node.replaceChild(child, newName);
      } else {
        replaceReferencesToThis(child, name);
      }
    }
  }

  public boolean hasProperty(String name) {
    return super.hasProperty(name) || "prototype".equals(name);
  }

  boolean defineProperty(String name, JSType type,
      boolean inferred, boolean inExterns) {
    if ("prototype".equals(name)) {
      ObjectType objType = type.toObjectType();
      if (objType != null) {
        return setPrototype(
            new FunctionPrototypeType(
                registry, this, objType, isNativeObjectType()));
      } else {
        return false;
      }
    }
    return super.defineProperty(name, type, inferred, inExterns);
  }
```

But note: `Node[] children = node.children().toArray(new Node[0]);` may not compile because `node.children()` returns an `Iterable`? Actually, in the Closure Compiler AST, `Node.children()` returns a `List<Node>` so we can do `node.children().toArray(new Node[0])`. That should work.

Alternatively, use an indexed loop: `for (int i = 0; i < node.getChildCount(); i++) { Node child = node.getChildAtIndex(i); ... }` which is safe because we are not modifying the index. But using `node.replaceChild` modifies the list, so indexed loop would also break because indices shift. The safest is to collect all children into a list first, then iterate over that list, replacing in the original node's children list. That is what we did.

